title: Legislative Council Question No.8 (Written Reply)
question_text:
Date of Sitting: 6 December 2000 Asked by: Hon. CHAN Yuen-han
Replied by: Secretary for Health and Welfare Question : It is learnt that between June last year and August this year, there were 916 cases in which the Comprehensive Social Security Assistance ("CSSA") recipients who had participated in the Active Employment Assistance Programme ceased to receive CSSA payments after obtaining

employment. In this connection, will the Government inform this Council: (a) of a breakdown of these cases by: (i) age band and gender of the recipients, as well as household size; (ii) the number of children aged 12 or below in the recipient families; (iii) post, trade and duration of employment in respect of the jobs found by the recipients; (b) of the average monthly salary for the jobs found by the recipients;  (c) of the number of cases in which the recipients became unemployed again after finding jobs; and (d) whether the Social

Welfare Department had arranged for the recipients concerned to attend courses organized by the Employees Retraining Board which were related to the jobs subsequently found by the recipients; if not, of the reasons for these recipients still being able to find these jobs?
reply_text:
Madam President, On the basis of

participants of the Active Employment Assistance (AEA) Programme who have ceased receiving
CSSA payment after securing gainful employment is given below:  (a) (i) Breakdown of profile of those participants <u>Age</u> <u>%</u> 15-24 13 25-34 13 35-44 37 45-54 30 55-59* 7 * CSSA recipients of 60 or above

(b) The average monthly salary for the above jobs is estimated at around $7,260**.  ** For those paid daily and hourly, it is assumed that they work eight hours a day and 20 days a month to arrive at their respective monthly salary.  (c) A survey has just been completed to follow up on the employment situation of CSSA recipients who reported having secured a job

during the first year of implementation of the Support for Self-reliance Scheme. We should
be able to provide the requested information in the near future. (d) Social Welfare Department will as appropriate refer AEA participants to Employees Retraining Board (ERB) training courses.
Starting from October 2000, arrangements have been made to collect information on training
courses attended by AEA participants with breakdowns by whether the participants have been
successful in job search. We do not have data from previous periods and at present the
period of data collection is too short to allow meaningful analysis of the figures.
